  <h1>What to Do After an ADA Violation</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Riley Chen (RC), Employment &amp; Civil Rights Practice Lead. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>1. Document everything immediately</h2>
  <p>Write a detailed contemporaneous account of what happened, including dates, times, who was present, and exactly what was said. Save all relevant emails, texts, performance reviews, and HR communications. If you made a written accommodation request, keep a copy. Document any medical documentation you provided. Courts and the EEOC look for contemporaneous records &mdash; they are far more credible than recollections written months later.</p>
  <h2>2. Continue following workplace procedures</h2>
  <p>Do not quit your job unless the conditions are intolerable (constructive discharge). Continue performing your job duties and following workplace policies. Courts expect plaintiffs to mitigate damages &mdash; leaving voluntarily can reduce your back pay claim significantly.</p>
  <h2>3. File an EEOC charge promptly</h2>
  <p>For Title I (employment) claims, you must file a charge of discrimination with the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission within <strong>180 days</strong> of the violation (or <strong>300 days</strong> in states with a Fair Employment Practices Agency). This deadline is strict &mdash; missing it usually bars your claim. You can file online at eeoc.gov, by mail, or in person at an EEOC field office.</p>
  <h2>4. Understand the EEOC process</h2>
  <p>After filing, the EEOC may investigate, attempt mediation, or issue a right-to-sue letter relatively quickly. Once you receive the right-to-sue letter, you have <strong>90 days</strong> to file in federal court. You can also request an early right-to-sue letter if you want to proceed to court without waiting for the EEOC investigation to conclude.</p>
  <h2>5. Consult an employment attorney</h2>
  <p>ADA cases involve complex procedural requirements and damages calculations. Most employment attorneys take ADA cases on contingency (no fee unless you win). An attorney can evaluate your claim, handle the EEOC process, and maximize your recovery. Consult one as early as possible &mdash; before the EEOC deadline if you can.</p>
  <h2>6. For Title II and Title III claims</h2>
  <p>Government services (Title II) and public accommodations (Title III) claims can be filed directly in federal court or with the DOJ Civil Rights Division. There is no EEOC exhaustion requirement for these claims. Statutes of limitations vary by state (typically 2&ndash;4 years).</p>
  <h2>Where to go from here</h2>
  <p>See <a href="/guides/how-ada-damages-are-calculated">how ADA damages are calculated</a> and <a href="/guides/common-ada-claim-misconceptions">common ADA claim misconceptions</a>.</p>
